# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-flag-rugby
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:american-flag-rugby/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] McGill football game** was a two-game series between the Harvard Crimson and the McGill Redmen held in Cambridge, Massachusetts, on May 14 and 15, 1874.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] With the first game being played under the Harvard's "Boston game", the second one was the first rugby-style football game played in the United States.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] It used three periods or "games" and ended in a scoreless tie.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Rutgers football game had been played five years earlier (in 1869), but under a variation of England's The Football Association rules, closer to contemporary soccer than American football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The Boston game rules were developed by the first organized football team, the Oneida Football Club, founded in 1862.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Many of its members went on to found, and play for, the Harvard team.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] On October 20, 1873, representatives from Yale, Columbia, Princeton, and Rutgers met at the Fifth Avenue Hotel in New York City to codify the first set of intercollegiate football rules.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Before this meeting, each school had its own set of rules and games were usually played using the home team's own particular code.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] At this meeting, a list of rules, based more on association football than on rugby football, was drawn up for intercollegiate football games.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Harvard, which played the Boston game, a version of football that allowed carrying, refused to attend this rules conference and continued to play under its own code.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] While Harvard's voluntary absence from the meeting made it hard for them to schedule games against other American universities, it agreed to a challenge to play McGill University, from Montreal, Canada, in a two-game series.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The McGill team traveled to Cambridge to meet Harvard.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] On May 14, 1874, the first game, played under Boston rules, was dominated by Harvard, which lead 3–0 after only 22 minutes when the game was ended.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The next day, the two teams played under "McGill" rugby rules to a scoreless tie.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The first game featured a round ball instead of a rugby-style oblong ball.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] McGill used a bladder covered by leather instead of a rubber ball as did Harvard, which was much more difficult to kick.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The game drew about 500 attendees, most of whom were students.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] This series of games represents an important milestone in the development of the modern games of Canadian and American football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] A similar game was played a year later between Harvard and Tufts establishing this as the first game between two American colleges played under rules used in today's version of American football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] At this time, the try was not used in American football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The try would later evolve into the score known as the touchdown.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] In late 1874, the Harvard team traveled to Montreal to play McGill in rugby, and won by three tries in front of 2,000 spectators.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The **Stanford rugby teams of 1906 to 1917** represented Stanford University as the school's only football program during those years, replacing American football with rugby union.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The school had played American football from 1892 to 1905, but in 1906, concerned with the growing levels of violence in football, Stanford and other universities changed to rugby.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford played twelve seasons of rugby, during which it played other college teams, club teams from the United States, Canada, and Australia, as well as the New Zealand national team and Australia national team.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] American football in the early 1900s had become increasingly violent; with no forward pass, the ball carrier would be typically pushed and pulled up the field by his own players in massive formations that often resulted in serious injuries.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In 1905, 18 deaths, three at the college level, were attributed to football; 159 serious injuries were also reported, 88 at the college level.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Reform was demanded by such voices as U.S.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] President Theodore Roosevelt, who decried the brutality and foul play of the game, and called a meeting of school presidents to discuss the issue.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] As a result, before the next season began, new rules were put in place to discourage such play.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The forward pass was also introduced to open up the game and reduce the role of dangerous mass formations.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Despite the planned changes, a number of universities banned the sport for the coming year, including Columbia, NYU, and Northwestern.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Several universities on the West Coast, led by California and Stanford, replaced the sport with rugby.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] At the time, the future of football was very much in doubt and these schools believed that rugby would eventually be adopted nationwide.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Other schools that made the switch included Nevada, St.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] However, due to the perception that West Coast football was inferior to the game played on the East Coast anyway, East Coast and Midwest teams shrugged off the loss of the teams and continued playing football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] With no nationwide movement, the available pool of rugby teams to play remained small.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The schools scheduled games against local club teams and reached out to rugby powers in Australia, New Zealand, and especially, due to its proximity, Canada.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The annual Big Game between Stanford and California continued as rugby, with the winner invited by the British Columbia Rugby Union to a tournament in Vancouver over the Christmas holidays, with the winner of that tournament receiving the Cooper Keith Trophy.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In 12 seasons of rugby, Stanford was remarkably successful: the team had three undefeated seasons, three one-loss seasons, and an overall record of 94 wins, 20 losses, and 3 ties for a winning percentage of .816.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] However, after a few years, the school began to feel the isolation of its newly adopted sport, which was not spreading as many had hoped.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Students and alumni began to clamor for a return to football to allow wider intercollegiate competition.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The pressure at rival California was stronger (especially as the school had not been as successful in the Big Game as they had hoped), and in 1915 California returned to football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] As reasons for the change, the school cited football rule changes, the overwhelming desire of students and supporters to play football, interest in playing other East Coast and Midwest schools, and a patriotic desire to play an "American" game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] California's return to football increased the pressure on Stanford to also change back in order to maintain the rivalry.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford played its 1915, 1916, and 1917 "Big Games" as rugby against Santa Clara and California's football "Big Game" in those years was against Washington, but both schools desired to restore the old traditions.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The onset of World War I gave Stanford an out: in 1918, the Stanford campus was designated as the Students' Army Training Corps headquarters for all of California, Nevada, and Utah, and the commanding officer, Sam M.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Parker, decreed that football was the appropriate athletic activity to train soldiers and rugby was dropped.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] After the war, Stanford resumed its football program and relegated rugby to a minor sport.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Several Stanford rugby players who played during those years—including Daniel Carroll, Dink Templeton, Morris Kirksey, Erwin Righter, John Patrick, and Charles Doe—went on to win a gold medal for the United States in rugby at the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In its first season of rugby, Stanford retained head football coach James F.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Lanagan had coached the football team for three years, including an undefeated 1905 season.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] With no experience playing or coaching rugby, Lanagan initially offered his resignation, but Stanford insisted he stay on, so he traveled to Vancouver, British Columbia to study the sport.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford won its first five games, including two wins over a visiting club team from Vancouver.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] As winners of the first Big Game against California played as rugby, Stanford competed against Vancouver-area club teams for the Cooper Keith Trophy, losing two games and tying one.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In Stanford's second season of rugby, Jimmy Lanagan returned as coach and the team finished 8–4.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford continued its series with Nevada, Vancouver, and Victoria and added games against Bay Area club team the Barbarians and a Los Angeles club called the Castaways.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford won its second Big Game rugby match, earning a second straight tournament in British Columbia.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Lanagan returned for his final year as Stanford's coach and the team finished 12–2, winning not only its third consecutive Big Game, but also going on to win the Cooper Keith Trophy in the end-of-season Vancouver tournament.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford added two games against San Francisco's Olympic Club and played a final game against the Australian national team, the Wallabies.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Following Lanagan's departure, George Presley was named Stanford's new rugby coach.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Presley played one year of rugby under Lanagan in 1906 and had been an assistant coach in 1907 and 1908.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Presley also coached Stanford's baseball team.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford won its first eight games—seven by shutout—but then lost Big Game for the first time in seven years.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In Presley's second year as coach, Stanford was led by Ben Erb and Jim Arrell.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The season was almost identical to the previous year: the team won its first seven games by shutout, and then lost Big Game to undefeated California.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford led in that game 6–0, but did not score again as California won 25–6.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This Big Game is recognized as the first intercollegiate game to feature card stunts.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In the 1911 season, Stanford went 10–3 and added USC to the schedule, as the school dropped football in favor of rugby.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In Presley's last year as coach, Stanford finished with a 5–3–1 record, its worst record of the rugby era.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford avoided a fourth straight loss in the Big Game by tying California.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Despite an outstanding 30–8–1 overall record as coach, coach Presley was 0–3–1 against the Bears.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Brown succeeded George Presley as coach.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Like Presley, Brown had played for and served as an assistant under the previous coach.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford finished with an 8–3 record, including its first Big Game win in five years, led by Danny Carroll, who had won a gold medal in the 1908 Summer Olympics as a member of the Australia national rugby union team and who was now earning a degree in geology from Stanford.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford played its final rugby game against USC, who returned to American football the next year, and suffered two blowout losses to the famed New Zealand All Blacks, who were on a North American tour.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Brown's second year as coach was the best in Stanford rugby history: the team was undefeated entering the Big Game at California, who was also undefeated.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] A record crowd of 26,000 turned out to see Stanford defeat the Bears, 26–8.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This would be the last Big Game for several years as California returned to football for the 1915 season.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Despite Stanford's success in rugby, the previous year's humiliating defeats to the All Blacks and the switch by rivals USC and California to football intensified the sentiment for Stanford to switch back as well.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] By 1915, there was only one other U.S. college playing intercollegiate rugby: Santa Clara.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The rest of Stanford's schedule was made up of local club and all star teams.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The team played to a scoreless tie with the Olympic Club team to start the season, but recovered to win the rest of the games on the schedule.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In their last full season of rugby, Stanford won all its games except the "Big Game" against Santa Clara, played for the second year at Ewing Field in San Francisco.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This was Stanford's first loss since 1913.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Like the two coaches before him, Stanford's new head coach Jim Wylie was a former Stanford player.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] He had also been a member of the New Zealand All Blacks team that had crushed Stanford's team in 1913.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] But with World War I imminent, Stanford played just one game, the "Big Game" against Santa Clara, winning 15–11.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This was also Stanford rugby's last game as a major sport.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The following year, Stanford president Ray Lyman Wilbur canceled all intercollegiate athletic events due to students' enlisting in the military for the war, and due to Stanford's designation as the regional headquarters of the Students' Army Training Corps.
[src:american-flag-rugby/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] When Stanford reformed a team in 1919, the school returned to American football as its major gridiron sport.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] The **2018 Rugby World Cup Sevens** was the seventh edition of the Rugby World Cup Sevens.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Organized by World Rugby, it was held at AT&T Park, now known as Oracle Park, in San Francisco, United States.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] A total of 84 matches were played over three days from July 20–22, 2018.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] The men's tournament had 24 teams and the women's tournament 16, with both tournaments being played for the first time in a knock-out only format.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] New Zealand won the championship for both events — defeating England in the men's final and France in the women's final.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] USA Rugby selected the San Francisco Bay Area as the host candidate.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] The venue was AT&T Park, home to the San Francisco Giants of Major League Baseball.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] When the event was awarded to the Bay Area in May 2015, Avaya Stadium, home to the San Jose Earthquakes of Major League Soccer, was announced as a second venue.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] However, the following year, Avaya Stadium was dropped as a venue.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] The three-day tournament was the most-watched live rugby cast in the U.S. on record.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Day 2 coverage achieved a rating of 1.0, while Day 3 coverage attained a 1.1.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Coverage reached nine million viewers across NBC five telecasts, with finals day coverage averaging 1.365 million viewers.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Over 100,000 fans attended the three day event, which was a record-breaking crowd for a rugby event in the United States.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Over the three days of competition there was a total of 84 matches played across both the men's and women's competitions.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] All times in Pacific Daylight Time (UTC−07:00).
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Twenty four teams participate in the men's World Cup Sevens.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Nine teams automatically qualify — eight by reaching the quarterfinals at the 2013 Rugby World Cup Sevens, and one host nation.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Additionally, the top four teams not already qualified from the 2016–17 World Sevens Series also qualify.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] The remaining 11 teams qualify through continental qualifiers — two from each of the six regions, except North America which gets only one additional place.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Sixteen teams play at the women's World Cup Sevens.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Four teams automatically qualified by reaching the semifinals at the 2013 Rugby World Cup Sevens.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] Additionally, the top four teams not already qualified from the 2016–17 Women's World Sevens Series also qualified.
[src:american-flag-rugby/2018-rugby-world-cup-sevens] The remaining eight places will be filled via continental qualifiers.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:american-flag-rugby/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] The **American 7s Football League** (**A7FL**) is a sports league in the United States which plays a seven-man version of gridiron football called American 7s Football.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Launched in 2015, its games are played without football helmets or other protective equipment.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] League players are not paid during the season and most of them are primarily amateurs.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Instead cash prizes are awarded to division and national champs (divided among the roster of roughly 25 players).
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] For the 2022 season the prize pool was $50,000.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Founded in 2014 with play commencing the following year, the A7FL plays a seven-game schedule running from March to May, with playoffs running from June to July.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] It can trace it history to a New York metropolitan area league called **Town Beef** that started in 2008 and played 7-on-7 full-contact football with no helmets or pads.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] North Jersey remains one of the two nuclei around which the A7FL's teams are based, the other being the Las Vegas Valley.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] The league primarily attracts semi-professional football players seeking opportunities to stay in shape during spring.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2016, the league participated in a safety study led by the New Jersey Institute of Technology.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2023, the league had its first former NFL starter sign with a team, that being cornerback Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie, who signed with the Tampa Nightcrawlers.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] A7FL players play without pads or helmets as part of what the league describes as an effort to reduce the potential of head injuries resulting from helmet-to-helmet contact.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] League games also do not include kickoffs, field goals, or punts, and, instead of the kickoff, implement a unique version of special teams called a 3-on-1 throw off (three 'throwing' players and one receiver).
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Games are played on narrow fields of 37 yards' width (34 m, between one set of hash marks and the furthest sideline away) to accommodate fewer players on the field on each team.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] A7FL games are played between two seven-man teams; teams are, additionally, required to cap their rosters at 35 active players.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Teams that will participate in the 2026 season.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Eleven Sports Network acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to broadcast the A7FL 2017 Championship on July 9, 2017, played at Palisades Credit Union Park.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Through Eleven Sports Network's distribution with DirecTV, Verizon FiOS, and AT&T uVerse the A7FL 2017 Championship was to be accessible by over 70 million homes worldwide.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2018, Eleven Sports Network acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to broadcast a 21-game package including the playoffs and championship, and in 2019, the non-exclusive U.S. and international rights to the playoffs and championship.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2019, Twitch acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to a 21-game package of the season including the playoffs and championship.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2020, A7FL again partnered with Eleven Sports Network for the exclusive United States and international rights of the season, including the playoffs and championship.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] For 2021, FITE TV acquired the United States and international rights to the A7FL's season including the playoffs and championship.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Starting in 2022, select Games of the Week -- including the playoffs and championship - were broadcast on Stadium (sports network), YouTube, DAZN, and A7FL.tv.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2025, select A7FL Games of the Week including the playoffs and championship and A7FL InMotion, a weekly 30 minute show featuring a look inside the A7FL -- are broadcast on Fox Soul, Stadium (sports network), DAZN, Triller TV, YouTube, and A7FL.tv.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] The CEO of the A7FL is Sener Korkusuz and its president is Ryan DePaul.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] In 2019, UFC co-founder David Isaacs joined the A7FL to serve as chairman of the advisory board.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Isaacs said, "Removing equipment to make any sport safer seems counterintuitive and we faced similar issues when we launched the UFC and created the sport of mixed martial arts.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] With the A7FL, football can be safer but still thrilling full-contact competition.
[src:american-flag-rugby/a7fl] Athletes playing in the A7FL are required to sign a player injury waiver and be 18 years of age or older.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The **Bowl Series Rugby**, formerly American Collegiate Rugby Championship (ACRC) Bowl Series, was an annual college rugby competition featuring top national teams playing fifteen-a-side rugby.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The inaugural event was held in Charlotte, N.C. in November 2014; this 20-team bowl competition occurred at Charlotte’s Rugby Athletic Center, a sports and events venue located three miles from downtown.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The tournament was managed by URugby, a division of Sevens Sports LLC, a sports event management and marketing company specializing in the sport of rugby.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2014 ACRC Bowl Series included nine collegiate bowl games with 18 teams (including nine conference champions) over two days.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Participating conference champions were Clemson, American International College, Stony Brook, Bowling Green, Life University, West Virginia, Army, South Carolina, and North Texas.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The AIC-Bowling Green game was named the 2014 College Game of the Year by *Goff Rugby Report*.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2015 ACRC Bowl Series were memorable, marked by close contests and dramatic finishes, including the down-to-the-wire Southeastern Collegiate Rugby Conference Championship and an Indiana-Kutztown game Alex Goff called an "instant classic".
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] With two tournament locations, The University of Delaware visited Iona College's campus for one of ten bowl matches in 2015 while mine other matches were held in Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] In 2016, the tournament changed its name to the Bowl Series Rugby.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] This created a more inclusive conference, which allowed high school 7s matches played during halftime of the collegiate 15s matches.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Hosted at Iona College, the 2016 Bowl Series produced more classic matches on its opening day than previous years as the hosts Iona College facing off with ECRC champions American International College (AIC) with "an aggressive, hard-charging defense".
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2016 Bowl Series returned to Iona College, New Rochelle, New York on November 19 and 20, for a 2-day 24-team collegiate championship event.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2016 Bowl Series hosted six collegiate 15s matches and six high school 7s matches.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Featuring six returning teams from the 2014 Bowl Series and the 2015 Bowl Series, the tournament guaranteed the electric passion of previous years.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Returning teams included: American International College, Iona College, Stony Brook University, Rutgers University, University of Delaware and University of Massachusetts.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2015 ACRC Bowl Series took place Nov 20-21.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The line-up of teams included the then-#1 and #2 ranked college rugby teams in the U.S., American International College and Indiana University, and five of the then-current Top 10.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Nine of the 10 matches took place at the Rugby Athletic Center in Charlotte.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The tenth, dubbed the Quinn For the Win Ice Bucket Challenge, took place at Iona College in New York.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The game between Iona College and the University of Delaware raised money for former rugby player and Ice Bucket Challenge co-founder Pat Quinn's Quinn For the Win foundation, which raises money for ALS research.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2015 Bowl Series was the site of the SCRC championship game between Tennessee and South Carolina.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Tennessee won the game with a dramatic last-minute try to secure the 23-22 victory.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The inaugural American Collegiate Rugby Championships Bowl Series came to Charlotte, N.C on November 21–23, 2014.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] This high-level collegiate rugby competition hosted a series of matches in traditional bowl format, bringing the very best college rugby teams from around the country to Charlotte’s Rugby Athletic Center.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] The 2014 ACRC Bowl Series featured eight championship bowl games over three days.
[src:american-flag-rugby/acrc-bowl-series] Many of the participating teams were selected based on their finish in their respective collegiate conferences.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] American flag rugby is divided up among four different levels based upon the grade level a child is entering.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] Each division itself has a unique set of rules in recognition that there will be different ability levels between the various age groups.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] The game, while based on rugby union, is actually far more related to rugby sevens.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] Similarities are seen with the number of players on the field and the arrangement of the line-outs, scrums and kick-offs.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] Like rugby union, games are played in halves but the halves are significantly reduced.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] The halves are the same for all four levels at 10 minutes each instead of 40 minutes each.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] The rule differences between each division are minor and gradually shift closer towards rugby union rules as the child advances up in divisions and increases his or her skill set.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] For Owls the game typically revolves around teaching the children to run with the ball, learning to touch the ball down when scoring a try and learning basic passing skills.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] Nothing is contested, there is no kicking, and there are no conversions.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] However, when children reach the Eagle level, many of the prior mentioned restrictions are removed and the children play with contest are allowed open field kicking, and the game has a more dynamic flow to it.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] The first iteration of American flag rugby was founded by Tom Feury in 1998.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] Feury was initially looking for nothing more than a way to get his children and their friends introduced to the game.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] In 1999, the town of Denville granted him access to a field in order to do so.
[src:american-flag-rugby/american-flag-rugby] The first year began with only one team and 28 children.
